      Wrestling bets
   =20
 =20

Oh man, I am so excited to write about  this insider trading case in like a=
 year:

[World Wrestling Entertainment Inc.] is in talks with state gambling regula=
tors in Colorado and Michigan to legalize betting on high-profile matches, =
according to people familiar with the matter.
WWE is working with the accounting firm EY to secure scripted match results=
 in hopes it will convince regulators there=E2=80=99s no chance of results =
leaking to the public, said the people, who asked not to be named because t=
he discussions are private. Accounting firms PwC and EY, also known as Erns=
t & Young, have historically worked with award shows, including the Academy=
 Awards and the Emmys, to keep results a secret.
Betting on the Academy Awards is already legal and available through some s=
ports betting applications, including market leaders FanDuel and DraftKings=
, although most states don=E2=80=99t allow it. WWE executives have cited Os=
cars betting as a template to convince regulators gambling on scripted matc=
hes is safe, the people said.

So you have two problems here. One is the risk of insider betting: The writ=
ers write a script for the match, and then they tell the wrestlers and refe=
rees and announcers and anyone else who needs to know what the script will =
look like, and then maybe there=E2=80=99s a rehearsal or whatever, I don=E2=
=80=99t know, I don=E2=80=99t watch a ton of wrestling, but the point is th=
at if you have scripted results for a wrestling match then some people need=
 to know those results before the match =E2=80=94=C2=A0so they can produce =
the results! =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there are security issues. The way to minim=
ize those issues is to (1) tell the people at the last minute and (2) cut o=
ff betting once you tell them, so even if there=E2=80=99s a leak no one can=
 bet on it.
The other problem is the risk of match fixing. I mean, it=E2=80=99s all fix=
ed, but you know what I mean: What you don=E2=80=99t want is for someone to=
 bet on the results of a match and then influence that result by, for insta=
nce, bribing the writers. (Or by=C2=A0being=C2=A0one of the writers, for th=
at matter, and betting anonymously on an outcome that you can script.) The =
way to minimize=C2=A0that=C2=A0issue is to (1) write the outcome long in ad=
vance and (2) open betting only after the outcome is determined.
Those things conflict, but here you go:

In discussions about how gambling on wrestling could work, WWE executives h=
ave proposed that scripted results of matches be locked in months ahead of =
time, according to people familiar with the matter. The wrestlers themselve=
s wouldn=E2=80=99t know whether they were winning or losing until shortly b=
efore a match takes place, said the people.
For example, the WWE could lock the results of Wrestlemania=E2=80=99s main =
event months ahead of time, based on a scripted storyline that hinged to th=
e winner of January=E2=80=99s Royal Rumble. Betting on the match could then=
 take place between the end of the Royal Rumble and up to days or even hour=
s before Wrestlemania, when the wrestlers and others in the show=E2=80=99s =
production would learn the results.

Somebody=C2=A0needs to know the outcome months before the match, but that k=
nowledge needs to be closely guarded until hours before the match. Seems ha=
rd. I love it. Also:
If WWE succeeds in its bid to legalize gambling on matches, it could open t=
he door for legalized betting on other guarded, secret scripted events, suc=
h as future character deaths in TV series.
It seems arbitrary to be able to bet only on events that occur in the real =
world. Why not bet on fictional sports too.

