<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Silvergate</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can, with hindsight, do some dumb math abo=
ut Silvergate Capital Corp., the crypto-friendly bank that melted this mont=
h. At the end of September, various crypto companies had about $12 billion =
of deposits at Silvergate.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Silvergate=E2=80=99s interest expense on those deposits was $0.00 per =
year: Those were non-interest-bearing demand=C2=A0deposits; crypto firms ke=
pt their money at Silvergate for transactional and convenience reasons, not=
 to earn interest, and they didn=E2=80=99t.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3078=
4666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjM=
tMDMtMDIvc2lsdmVyZ2F0ZS1oYWQtYS1jcnlwdG8tYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwOTIzX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjMwMzA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbaa5f2=
85" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about Silvergate, and its Silvergate Ex=
change Network for crypto transactions.) Silvergate did have some other exp=
enses; its noninterest expense (salaries, rent, etc.) for 2022 totaled abou=
t $123 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late September 2022, <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly9mcmVkLnN0bG91=
aXNmZWQub3JnL3Nlcmllcy9ER1MxTU8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB276bae66" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 one-month Treasury bills</a> were yielding more than 2.5%. The dumb math i=
s, you take the $12 billion of deposits, you buy $12 billion of bills, and =
you get paid $300 million a year in interest. You pay your $123 million of =
non-interest expense, your $0 of interest expense, you have like $177 milli=
on left over as profit. Your assets are super-safe and super-liquid; if any=
 depositors ever want their money back you just sell a Treasury bill and gi=
ve it to them. This is an easy life.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not in fact what Silvergate did. It pu=
t its money into stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0real estate loans, muni bonds and mor=
tgage-backed securities and longer-dated Treasuries =E2=80=94=C2=A0that had=
 longer duration. And then interest rates went up, so the market value of t=
hat stuff went down. Silvergate=E2=80=99s actual net income for 2022 was <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMTIxMDkvMDAwMTMxMjEwOTI=
zMDAwMDIwL2V4OTkxc2k0cTIyZWFybmluZ3NyZWxlYXNlLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB04a02387" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> negative $949 million</a>, driven mostly by an $886 mi=
llion realized loss on its bond portfolio, though also by a $196 million wr=
ite-down=C2=A0of =E2=80=9Ccertain developed technology assets related to ru=
nning a block-chain-based payment network=E2=80=9D=C2=A0that it had bought =
in January 2022, oops.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile crypto firms were withdrawing billio=
ns of dollars of deposits from Silvergate over the last few months of 2022 =
and the first few months of 2023. Maybe a little of this was because they c=
ould earn higher interest on their money elsewhere? But a lot of it was bec=
ause they were crypto firms and the end of 2022 was horrible for crypto, wi=
th the collapse of the FTX exchange: The crypto markets went down, people t=
ook their money out, and a lot of their money was at Silvergate. If you had=
 an account at a crypto exchange, there=E2=80=99s a good chance that the ex=
change banked with Silvergate, and if you closed your account and cashed ou=
t, the cash came from a deposit at Silvergate. When lots of people closed t=
heir accounts and cashed out, that created a run on Silvergate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that is what led to the $886 million loss =
on Silvergate=E2=80=99s bond portfolio: It had to sell a bunch of bonds to =
pay out the depositors, and those bonds had lost value since it had bought =
them, because interest rates had gone up. If you borrow short (a bunch of d=
eposits from flighty crypto firms) and lend long (buying long-dated mortgag=
e-backed securities, etc.), that is the risk that you take: Rates go up, pe=
ople ask for their money back, you have to sell your assets, but they have =
lost value and you are out of money.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silvergate is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDgvc2lsdmVyZ2F0ZS1wbGFucy10by13aW5kLWRvd24tY=
mFuay1vcGVyYXRpb25zLWFuZC1saXF1aWRhdGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYm=
dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzA5JnV=
0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB74e6a018" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  more or less out of money</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silvergate Capital Corp. plans to wind down op=
erations and liquidate its bank after the crypto industry=E2=80=99s meltdow=
n sapped the company=E2=80=99s financial strength, sending shares plunging.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn light of recent industry and regul=
atory developments, Silvergate believes that an orderly wind down of bank o=
perations and a voluntary liquidation of the bank is the best path forward,=
=E2=80=9D the company said in a statement late Wednesday. =E2=80=9CThe bank=
=E2=80=99s wind-down and liquidation plan includes full repayment of all de=
posits.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silvergate collapsed amid scrutiny from regula=
tors and a criminal investigation by the Justice Department=E2=80=99s fraud=
 unit into dealings with fallen crypto giants FTX and Alameda Research. Tho=
ugh no wrongdoing was asserted, Silvergate=E2=80=99s woes deepened as the b=
ank sold off assets at a loss and shut its flagship payments network, which=
 it called =E2=80=9Cthe heart=E2=80=9D of its group of services for crypto =
clients.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, to be clear, I am being=C2=A0<em>very=C2=
=A0</em>unfair here. Treasury bills were yielding more than 2.5% in Septemb=
er 2022 (and more than 4.5% today), but they yielded roughly nothing from a=
bout March 2020 until about March 2022; Silvergate could not really have ru=
n itself as a profitable super-safe business in a zero-rates environment. I=
t needed to stretch at least a little bit somewhere =E2=80=94=C2=A0on credi=
t or duration =E2=80=94=C2=A0to earn enough interest to pay its costs. It s=
tretched on duration, and that hurt it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also=C2=A0Silvergate did not spring up out of =
nowhere in September 2022 to serve as a crypto bank; it <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjL=
mdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMTIxMDkvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTE5Mjg4NTEyL2Q1Njg2=
MTZkNDI0YjQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb11baa2a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> grew out of a =
regular bank</a> that =E2=80=9Cprovided financial services including commer=
cial banking, business lending, commercial and residential real estate lend=
ing and mortgage warehouse lending, all funded primarily by interest bearin=
g deposits and borrowings,=E2=80=9D and started its pivot to crypto in 2013=
. If you were building a crypto bank from scratch in September 2022, or tod=
ay, you might choose the simplest safest possible model. But if you slowly =
morphed a real estate bank into a crypto bank over years, you might be too =
slow to get rid of, like, your mortgage portfolio.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still the story of the end of Silvergate is <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zaWx2ZXJnYXRlcy1zdG9yeS1pcy1hYm91dC1mdW5=
kYW1lbnRhbHMtbm90LWp1c3QtY3J5cHRvLTMwZjA4ZmM2P21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczQ/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d899b9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> just sort of boring and normal</a>? I=
t had an incredibly simple, boring, old-school and=C2=A0<em>reasonably safe=
=C2=A0</em>banking business model, borrowing short and lending long, taking=
 demand deposits at low interest rates and investing the money in a fairly =
conservative portfolio of longer-maturity mortgages and bonds.=C2=A0What br=
ought down Silvergate is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When interest rates go up rapidly, if =
your assets are all long-dated bonds, they will go down in value.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Traditionally, banks deal with this risk by=
 holding their assets to maturity and not marking them to market: If you ha=
ve a 10-year loan and interest rates go up, the loan=E2=80=99s market value=
 goes down, but if you just wait 10 years you=E2=80=99ll be repaid in full =
and it=E2=80=99s no problem.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Silvergate, however,=C2=A0<em>als=
o=C2=A0</em>lost most of its deposits because its depositors were mostly cr=
ypto firms and crypto collapsed. It couldn=E2=80=99t hold its assets to mat=
urity, because it had a sudden huge need for cash to pay out those deposito=
rs. So it had to sell the assets, so it lost money, which left it thinly ca=
pitalized, which led to more depositors leaving, which led to more asset sa=
les, which ended Silvergate.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDkvc2lsdmVyZ2F0ZS1iZXQtZXZlcnl0aGluZy1vbi1jcnlwdG8tdGhlbi1=
3YXRjaGVkLWl0LWV2YXBvcmF0ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMDkmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdaf24f9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here=E2=80=99=
s Sheila Bair</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSilvergate=E2=80=99s trou=
bles are as much if not more about traditional banking risks =E2=80=94 lack=
 of diversification, maturity mismatches =E2=80=94 as it is about its expos=
ure to crypto,=E2=80=9D said Sheila Bair, who headed the FDIC during the gl=
obal financial crisis.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s right, but the =E2=80=9Cexposur=
e to crypto=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>the =E2=80=9Clack of diversific=
ation,=E2=80=9D and the lack of diversification was in Silvergate=E2=80=99s=
 liabilities, not its assets. If you set up a boring normal bank to provide=
 deposit banking for the widget industry, and all of your deposits come fro=
m the widget industry, and all of your investments are boring normal safe b=
onds and loans, and then (1) rates go up and (2) the widget industry vanish=
es overnight, your bank will be in trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about this story is that the =
crypto boom was itself=C2=A0a low-interest-rate phenomenon =E2=80=94=C2=A0p=
eople got into crypto speculation because bank accounts paid zero interest,=
 etc. =E2=80=94 and so Silvergate was=C2=A0<em>hugely=C2=A0</em>exposed to =
interest-rate risk. Its assets were rate-sensitive, and when rates went up =
they lost value. But its deposits were all from crypto, and=C2=A0<em>when r=
ates went up crypto collapsed=C2=A0</em>and took Silvergate=E2=80=99s depos=
its with it. In hindsight, Silvergate=E2=80=99s risk management a year ago =
should have been laser-focused on the risk of rising interest rates crushin=
g both its assets and its customers, and it should have, you know, bought a=
 lot of swaps? Put all the money in Treasury bills? Found some non-crypto d=
epositors?=C2=A0Shorted Bitcoin?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way to think about this story is that =
the dumb idea I started with =E2=80=94=C2=A0take deposits from crypto custo=
mers, don=E2=80=99t pay interest, keep the money somewhere safe and liquid =
=E2=80=94 is <em>so obvious</em>, and yet the history of crypto banking is =
about people not doing it.=C2=A0We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMDYvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXN0b2NrLWlzLW9uLXNhbGU_Y=
21waWQ9QkJEMDMwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5l=
d3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBf4f1453e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked the other day</a> about Tether, t=
he stablecoin issuer, which has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXRoZXIudG8vZW4vdHJhbnNwYXJlbmN5L=
w/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd0443f02" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> more than $70 billion</a> of,=
 let=E2=80=99s say, non-interest-bearing dollar deposits from crypto invest=
ors. =E2=80=9CIn principle,=E2=80=9D I wrote, Tether=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chas an e=
xtremely simple business model=E2=80=9D: Take those $70 billion of deposits=
, invest them in the safest simplest shortest-dated possible things, earn a=
 tiny bit of interest on a huge pile of money, keep all of it, and pay itse=
lf gobs of money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That <em>is </em>kind of what Tether does, but=
 also kind of not: It does stuff like make loans collateralized by Bitcoin,=
 and otherwise seems to take risks that=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>personally wou=
ld not take with a $70 billion pile of non-interest-bearing deposits. And t=
he reason for this is basically that Tether is not actually a bank, and it =
has somewhat fraught relationships with the global banking system, and so i=
t keeps finding itself doing stuff that a bank wouldn=E2=80=99t do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Silvergate is a bank! You would think that=
 someone with a banking license could find a way to take a bunch of deposit=
s from crypto firms who are desperate for banking, not pay them interest, a=
nd make money. It=E2=80=99s apparently harder than it sounds though.</p>
