<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh man, I am so excited to write about <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30784666.257406/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMy8wMy8wOC93d2UtYmV0dGluZy1zY3JpcHRlZC1tYXRjaC1yZXN1=
bHRzLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11acb1a3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this insider tradin=
g case</a> in like a year:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[World Wrestling Entertainment Inc.] is in tal=
ks with state gambling regulators in Colorado and Michigan to legalize bett=
ing on high-profile matches, according to people familiar with the matter.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">WWE is working with the accounting firm EY to =
secure scripted match results in hopes it will convince regulators there=E2=
=80=99s no chance of results leaking to the public, said the people, who as=
ked not to be named because the discussions are private. Accounting firms P=
wC and EY, also known as Ernst &amp; Young, have historically worked with a=
ward shows, including the Academy Awards and the Emmys, to keep results a s=
ecret.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Betting on the Academy Awards is already legal=
 and available through some sports betting applications, including market l=
eaders FanDuel and DraftKings, although most states don=E2=80=99t allow it.=
 WWE executives have cited Oscars betting as a template to convince regulat=
ors gambling on scripted matches is safe, the people said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you have two problems here. One is the risk=
 of insider betting: The writers write a script for the match, and then the=
y tell the wrestlers and referees and announcers and anyone else who needs =
to know what the script will look like, and then maybe there=E2=80=99s a re=
hearsal or whatever, I don=E2=80=99t know, I don=E2=80=99t watch a ton of w=
restling, but the point is that if you have scripted results for a wrestlin=
g match then some people need to know those results before the match =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0so they can produce the results! =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there are secu=
rity issues. The way to minimize those issues is to (1) tell the people at =
the last minute and (2) cut off betting once you tell them, so even if ther=
e=E2=80=99s a leak no one can bet on it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other problem is the risk of match fixing.=
 I mean, it=E2=80=99s all fixed, but you know what I mean: What you don=E2=
=80=99t want is for someone to bet on the results of a match and <em>then <=
/em>influence that result by, for instance, bribing the writers. (Or by=C2=
=A0<em>being=C2=A0</em>one of the writers, for that matter, and betting ano=
nymously on an outcome that you can script.) The way to minimize=C2=A0<em>t=
hat=C2=A0</em>issue is to (1) write the outcome long in advance and (2) ope=
n betting only after the outcome is determined.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those things conflict, but here you go:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In discussions about how gambling on wrestling=
 could work, WWE executives have proposed that scripted results of matches =
be locked in months ahead of time, according to people familiar with the ma=
tter. The wrestlers themselves wouldn=E2=80=99t know whether they were winn=
ing or losing until shortly before a match takes place, said the people.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, the WWE could lock the results of=
 Wrestlemania=E2=80=99s main event months ahead of time, based on a scripte=
d storyline that hinged to the winner of January=E2=80=99s Royal Rumble. Be=
tting on the match could then take place between the end of the Royal Rumbl=
e and up to days or even hours before Wrestlemania, when the wrestlers and =
others in the show=E2=80=99s production would learn the results.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Somebody=C2=A0</em>needs to know the outco=
me months before the match, but that knowledge needs to be closely guarded =
until hours before the match. Seems hard. I love it. Also:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If WWE succeeds in its bid to lega=
lize gambling on matches, it could open the door for legalized betting on o=
ther guarded, secret scripted events, such as future character deaths in TV=
 series.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seems arbitrary to be able to bet only on e=
vents that occur in the real world. Why not bet on fictional sports too.</p=
>
