round-color: #ccc;"> noted Marc Rubinstein last week</a>.) One possible ans=
wer is that Silvergate was in some sense insolvent =E2=80=94 its long-dated=
 assets were worth less than its liabilities, or at least its long-dated as=
sets were not worth enough to collateralize all the advances it needed =E2=
=80=94 so it couldn=E2=80=99t keep going sourcing liquidity from the FHLB. =
Another possible answer is that, for political or regulatory or other reaso=
ns, the FHLB didn=E2=80=99t want to keep lending to Silvergate.</p>
